# Bashly — Cursor Rules

## Project Identity
- Product: **Bashly** (`bashly.app`) — private event management SaaS
- Monorepo: Turborepo with `apps/web` (Next.js 14), `apps/mobile` (Expo 52), `packages/*`
- Blueprint reference: `event-saas-blueprint-v2.md` in project docs
- Brand reference: `bashly-brand-guidelines.html` in project docs
- Wireframe reference: `bashly-host-dashboard.html` and `guest-event-page.html` for UI patterns

---

## 1. Stack — Never Deviate

### Web (`apps/web`)
- **Framework:** Next.js 14, App Router only — never use Pages Router
- **Language:** TypeScript strict mode — `any` is never acceptable; always type everything
- **Styling:** Tailwind CSS v3 + shadcn/ui — never write plain CSS files or inline styles
- **Database:** Drizzle ORM + Neon PostgreSQL — never raw SQL strings, never Prisma
- **Auth:** Better Auth — never Clerk, never NextAuth, never custom JWT. All auth flows go through `@/libs/auth` (server) and `@/libs/auth-client` (client)
- **Forms:** React Hook Form + Zod — never uncontrolled inputs, never `useState` for form state
- **Email:** Resend + React Email — never nodemailer, never SendGrid
- **File storage:** Cloudflare R2 via `@aws-sdk/client-s3` — never `multer`, never local disk
- **Payments:** Stripe — already wired; extend, never replace

### Mobile (`apps/mobile`)
- **Framework:** Expo 52 + Expo Router — file-based routing, same mental model as Next.js App Router
- **Styling:** NativeWind v4 — same Tailwind class names as web, never `StyleSheet.create`
- **UI primitives:** React Native Reusables — never import from `@radix-ui/*` in mobile code
- **Auth:** `@better-auth/expo` + `expo-secure-store` — never `AsyncStorage` for auth tokens

### Shared (`packages/*`)
- `packages/types` — shared TypeScript interfaces and types
- `packages/validators` — shared Zod schemas used by both web forms and API validation
- `packages/api-client` — typed fetch wrappers for Bashly API endpoints
- `packages/tailwind-config` — single source of truth for design tokens; both apps extend this

---

## 2. Next.js Conventions

### Server vs Client Components
- Default to **Server Components**. Add `"use client"` only when strictly required:
  - Event handlers (`onClick`, `onChange`, etc.)
  - Hooks (`useState`, `useEffect`, `useRef`, etc.)
  - Browser APIs (`window`, `document`, `navigator`, etc.)
  - Mapbox GL JS (requires `"use client"` — WebGL)
  - Countdown timer components
- Never put `"use client"` on a layout or page unnecessarily

### Runtime
- API routes that use Better Auth, Stripe, or Cloudflare R2 must use **Node.js runtime** (default)
- Never add `export const runtime = 'edge'` to any route that touches auth, payments, or file storage
- Edge runtime is only appropriate for static middleware (already correct in `middleware.ts`)

### Route Structure
- All web routes live under `apps/web/src/app/[locale]/`
- Auth-required pages live inside `(auth)/` route group
- Public event pages: `(public)/e/[slug]/` — ISR, no auth, theme-aware
- Dashboard: `(auth)/dashboard/` — all host workspace routes

### Data Fetching
- Prefer `async` Server Components with direct Drizzle queries over API routes for dashboard data
- Use API routes only for: unauthenticated guest endpoints, streaming service OAuth, webhook handlers, presigned URL generation
- Always use `React.Suspense` + skeleton components for async data in layouts

### File Naming
- Files: `kebab-case` (e.g., `song-queue.tsx`, `use-rsvp-form.ts`)
- Components: `PascalCase` export (e.g., `export function SongQueue()`)
- Feature folders: `apps/web/src/features/[feature-name]/` for feature-specific components
- Shared components: `apps/web/src/components/` for truly reusable UI primitives

